WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.00 --> 00:00:02.28
There is also a massive winter storm

00:00:02.28 --> 00:00:05.25
that is likely to bring severe weather to nearly 30

00:00:05.25 --> 00:00:06.48
million Americans.

00:00:06.48 --> 00:00:08.27
It held yesterday in Southern California,

00:00:08.27 --> 00:00:09.39
which doesn't happen often.

00:00:09.39 --> 00:00:11.76
This is the Rose Bowl in Pasadena.

00:00:11.76 --> 00:00:13.98
And that system is moving east.

00:00:13.98 --> 00:00:16.14
Weather Channel meteorologist Stephanie Abrams

00:00:16.14 --> 00:00:18.90
joins us now from their global headquarters in Atlanta.

00:00:18.90 --> 00:00:22.11
Stephanie, give us some good news.

00:00:22.11 --> 00:00:24.44
Nate, I wish I could, but sadly, all that severe weather

00:00:24.44 --> 00:00:26.39
that you just showed is shifting east.

00:00:26.39 --> 00:00:28.18
And so as we head into the overnight hours,

00:00:28.18 --> 00:00:29.60
it looks like the Red River Valley

00:00:29.60 --> 00:00:32.28
is where we are going to see the threat for hail,

00:00:32.28 --> 00:00:33.45
damaging winds.

00:00:33.45 --> 00:00:35.30
And we also can't rule out tornadoes.

00:00:35.30 --> 00:00:36.68
I want to show you our Torcon.

00:00:36.68 --> 00:00:38.48
This is our tornado threat scale.

00:00:38.48 --> 00:00:39.78
It's a 3 out of 10 today.

00:00:39.78 --> 00:00:42.80
So that means that severe weather and tornadoes

00:00:42.80 --> 00:00:43.58
are possible.

00:00:43.58 --> 00:00:44.96
How about the timing of this?

00:00:44.96 --> 00:00:47.03
It's going to start as we head into the afternoon

00:00:47.03 --> 00:00:48.24
and into the evening hours.

00:00:48.24 --> 00:00:49.93
So watch out for those kids maybe

00:00:49.93 --> 00:00:51.80
being woken up by the lightning or the storms

00:00:51.80 --> 00:00:54.05
or maybe your pets hopping into bed with you

00:00:54.05 --> 00:00:55.76
because they're woken up by these storms.

00:00:55.76 --> 00:00:58.29
It continues to roll eastbound for our Thursday.

00:00:58.29 --> 00:01:00.44
So all day Thursday, it's going to be here

00:01:00.44 --> 00:01:02.06
throughout the Mississippi River Valley

00:01:02.06 --> 00:01:03.78
and deep into the Southeast.

00:01:03.78 --> 00:01:06.11
And it's not just those areas that could see the storms.

00:01:06.11 --> 00:01:09.83
It expands all the way up into the Midwest for tomorrow.

00:01:09.83 --> 00:01:12.23
And then there's a wintry side of this.

00:01:12.23 --> 00:01:13.79
We are going to see that snow-- look

00:01:13.79 --> 00:01:16.09
at this swath, 8 to 12 inches.

00:01:16.09 --> 00:01:19.58
In places like Kansas City, we could wipe out our deficit.

00:01:19.58 --> 00:01:22.28
We are nearly 6 inches below average.

00:01:22.28 --> 00:01:24.29
Nate, we'll have more from our expert team

00:01:24.29 --> 00:01:26.75
live throughout the storm on the Weather Channel television

00:01:26.75 --> 00:01:27.80
network.

00:01:27.80 --> 00:01:30.14
Let's keep those warm coats out, that's for sure.

00:01:30.14 --> 00:01:32.74
Stephanie Abrams, thank you so much.